\subsubsection{Project Social Media}

Official profiles were created on the following platforms: \textbf{LinkedIn} and \textbf{Mastodon}. These platforms serve as key communication channels to promote project activities and results, as well as share relevant content on pro-environmentalism in adolescence (e.g., podcasts, forums, and news). The selection of these networks is based on their ability to reach diverse audiences and foster meaningful engagement:

\begin{itemize}
  \item \textbf{LinkedIn} (\href{https://www.linkedin.com/in/terra-project-1698403a3}{www.linkedin.com/in/terra-project-1698403a3}): A professional network ideal for connecting with educators, policymakers, and organizations interested in sustainability and youth development. It enhances the project's visibility among institutional stakeholders and facilitates knowledge exchange.
  \item \textbf{Mastodon} (\href{https://mastodon.social/@terra_project}{mastodon.social/@terra\_project}): A decentralized social network that promotes open dialogue and community engagement. It aligns with the project's values of inclusivity and sustainability, offering an alternative to mainstream platforms and fostering discussions on environmental issues.
\end{itemize}

\subsubsection{Open Science Framework (OSF)}

The OSF platform (\href{https://osf.io/utmak/overview}{osf.io/utmak/overview}) will host protocols, datasets, and materials, ensuring open access and compliance with transparency standards. This reinforces the project's commitment to Open Science principles.

\subsubsection{Participation in Scientific Events and Publications}

The project will actively engage in national and international scientific events to disseminate findings and foster dialogue with the academic community. Participation in conferences and symposia (at least 4 presentations) will provide opportunities to present research outcomes, share methodologies, and strengthen collaborations with experts in sustainability and adolescent development. In parallel, the project will prioritize the publication of peer-reviewed articles (at least 4 articles) in high-impact journals to ensure scientific rigor and visibility.

\subsubsection{Infographics and Press Releases}

To reach non-academic audiences and ensure inclusivity, the project will produce visually engaging infographics summarizing key findings in accessible language. These materials will be tailored for adolescents, educators, and community stakeholders, promoting environmental awareness and practical actions. Press releases will be prepared for major milestones, such as the publication of significant results and the organization of events. Dissemination through media outlets and institutional channels will amplify the project's visibility and foster dialogue beyond the academic sphere.

\subsubsection{White Book and Closing Seminar}

The White Book will serve as a comprehensive legacy document, compiling the project's insights, best practices, and policy recommendations aimed at educators, decision-makers, and community stakeholders. It will synthesize research findings into actionable strategies to promote sustainability in adolescence, ensuring that the knowledge generated by the project remains accessible and impactful beyond its duration.

In addition, a Closing Seminar will be organized as a high-profile event to present the results, engage stakeholders, and foster dialogue on sustainability and youth engagement. This seminar will provide an opportunity to share lessons learned, celebrate achievements, and strengthen networks for future collaboration.

% ============================================================
\section{Monitoring}
% ============================================================

To ensure effectiveness, dissemination activities will be monitored through predefined indicators such as social media engagement, number of downloads from OSF, participation in events, and citation metrics. Regular reviews will allow adjustments to maximize impact and inclusivity.
